# Detecting Unreliable Information: Vetting Sources and Fact-Checking

**Context matters.** In the digital age, misinformation (false content shared without intent to deceive) and disinformation (deliberate deception) spread easily, especially via social media[\[1\]](https://help.unhcr.org/slovakia/safe-online/information/#:~:text=Misinformation%20is%20false%20or%20inaccurate,gets%20shared%20without%20malicious%20intent)[\[2\]](https://help.unhcr.org/slovakia/safe-online/information/#:~:text=Disinformation). It’s vital to question everything you read. A widely-shared library infographic (below) summarizes key checks: _“Consider the source”_, _“Read beyond”_ sensational headlines, _“Check the author”_, _“Check the date”_, and even _“Check your biases.”_ Each tip reminds us to verify details (who wrote it, why, and in what context) before trusting or sharing a story【65†】. Social networks and algorithms often amplify flashy or emotional content[\[3\]](https://help.unhcr.org/slovakia/safe-online/information/#:~:text=In%20both%20cases%2C%20social%20media,it%27s%20important%20to%20develop%20a), so slowing down to apply these checks can keep you from falling for fake news.

![](data:image/png;base64,)  
_Practical tips to “How to Spot Fake News.” For example, this infographic (IFLA/FactCheck.org) urges readers to_ _“consider the source”_ _(click away and inspect the publisher’s credibility),_ _“read beyond”_ _the headline (it may be clickbait),_ _“check the author”_ _(search their credentials),_ _“check the date”_ _(old stories may be outdated), and_ _“ask the experts”_ _(consult librarians or fact-checkers)【65†】. These steps help build a habit of verifying facts before believing or sharing information._

## Key Questions to Ask

When evaluating any claim or source, start by interrogating its origin. Ask questions like: **Who is behind this?** Check the author or organization’s identity and expertise[\[4\]](https://www.stevenson.edu/online/about-us/news/how-to-identify-reliable-information/#:~:text=1,that%20are%20up%20to%20date)[\[5\]](https://www.democracyandme.org/differentiating-between-reliable-and-unreliable-sources-in-a-fake-news-world/comment-page-1/#:~:text=Who%20wrote%20this%20source%3F%20What,I%20know%20from%20personal%20experience). Do they have credentials or a history of accuracy in this field? **Why was it published?** Consider the author’s purpose: educational, persuasive, or commercial[\[4\]](https://www.stevenson.edu/online/about-us/news/how-to-identify-reliable-information/#:~:text=1,that%20are%20up%20to%20date)[\[5\]](https://www.democracyandme.org/differentiating-between-reliable-and-unreliable-sources-in-a-fake-news-world/comment-page-1/#:~:text=Who%20wrote%20this%20source%3F%20What,I%20know%20from%20personal%20experience). A credible source will provide evidence and citations; a lack of references or an absence of data is a red flag. **What evidence is offered?** Reliable information is backed by verifiable facts or sources. Claims with _no_ links or citations, or that contradict well-known data, should be treated with suspicion[\[4\]](https://www.stevenson.edu/online/about-us/news/how-to-identify-reliable-information/#:~:text=1,that%20are%20up%20to%20date)[\[6\]](https://newslit.org/tips-tools/tool-type/infographic/#:~:text=3,algorithms%20to%20bring%20you%20updates). **Does it align with other sources?** One effective check is to see if respected outlets or experts report the same story. If multiple trustworthy news organizations or official bodies are covering it similarly, the claim is more likely accurate[\[7\]](https://help.unhcr.org/slovakia/safe-online/information/#:~:text=One%20of%20the%20best%20ways,such%20as%20%2054%20Google%E2%80%99s)[\[6\]](https://newslit.org/tips-tools/tool-type/infographic/#:~:text=3,algorithms%20to%20bring%20you%20updates). **When was it published?** Time-sensitive topics (like science or tech) require up-to-date information; an old article re-shared as new may be misleading[\[8\]](https://help.unhcr.org/slovakia/safe-online/information/#:~:text=,to%20provoke%20rather%20than%20inform).

*   Who wrote it? What are their credentials or background[\[4\]](https://www.stevenson.edu/online/about-us/news/how-to-identify-reliable-information/#:~:text=1,that%20are%20up%20to%20date)[\[5\]](https://www.democracyandme.org/differentiating-between-reliable-and-unreliable-sources-in-a-fake-news-world/comment-page-1/#:~:text=Who%20wrote%20this%20source%3F%20What,I%20know%20from%20personal%20experience)?
*   What is the author’s purpose or potential bias[\[4\]](https://www.stevenson.edu/online/about-us/news/how-to-identify-reliable-information/#:~:text=1,that%20are%20up%20to%20date)[\[5\]](https://www.democracyandme.org/differentiating-between-reliable-and-unreliable-sources-in-a-fake-news-world/comment-page-1/#:~:text=Who%20wrote%20this%20source%3F%20What,I%20know%20from%20personal%20experience)? (Are they selling something or pushing an agenda?)
*   Does the content cite evidence, data, or other credible sources[\[4\]](https://www.stevenson.edu/online/about-us/news/how-to-identify-reliable-information/#:~:text=1,that%20are%20up%20to%20date)[\[6\]](https://newslit.org/tips-tools/tool-type/infographic/#:~:text=3,algorithms%20to%20bring%20you%20updates)? If not, be skeptical.
*   Do other reputable outlets report the same information? (Cross-check with Google or news archives[\[7\]](https://help.unhcr.org/slovakia/safe-online/information/#:~:text=One%20of%20the%20best%20ways,such%20as%20%2054%20Google%E2%80%99s)[\[6\]](https://newslit.org/tips-tools/tool-type/infographic/#:~:text=3,algorithms%20to%20bring%20you%20updates).)
*   Is the information current and relevant? (Outdated details can be false in a new context[\[8\]](https://help.unhcr.org/slovakia/safe-online/information/#:~:text=,to%20provoke%20rather%20than%20inform).)
*   Might your own beliefs color your judgment? (Be aware of **confirmation bias** – our tendency to accept info that fits our views and reject the rest[\[9\]](https://newslit.org/tips-tools/tool-type/infographic/#:~:text=Image%3A%20Bias%20lesson%20cover%20art,often%20fail%20to%20notice%20them).)

## Misinformation vs. Disinformation

It helps to distinguish **misinformation** from **disinformation**[\[1\]](https://help.unhcr.org/slovakia/safe-online/information/#:~:text=Misinformation%20is%20false%20or%20inaccurate,gets%20shared%20without%20malicious%20intent)[\[2\]](https://help.unhcr.org/slovakia/safe-online/information/#:~:text=Disinformation). Misinformation is false or inaccurate info spread _without_ intent to deceive (often via misunderstanding or poor reporting). Disinformation is _deliberately_ false content crafted to mislead or manipulate (e.g. propaganda, hoaxes). Both can be dangerous. For example, UN advisors note that disinformation is “crafted to be believable” and can incite real-world harm[\[2\]](https://help.unhcr.org/slovakia/safe-online/information/#:~:text=Disinformation). In practice, treat any dubious claim with caution regardless of intent: verify its truth by checking impartial sources. One tip is to always consult **multiple independent sources**: if a story appears _only_ on fringe sites but not on major news organizations or official channels, it’s likely bogus[\[7\]](https://help.unhcr.org/slovakia/safe-online/information/#:~:text=One%20of%20the%20best%20ways,such%20as%20%2054%20Google%E2%80%99s). Likewise, real experts tend to **fact-check themselves** over time, whereas fake stories linger unchecked.

## Proven Evaluation Methods

Several systematic methods help streamline the vetting process:

*   **The CRAAP Test (Currency, Relevance, Authority, Accuracy, Purpose):** Librarians recommend asking whether the information is _current_, how _relevant_ it is to your needs, whether the _authority_ (author or publisher) is credible, whether the content is _accurate_ (well-cited and evidence-backed), and what the _purpose_ or agenda is[\[10\]](https://myjotbot.com/blog/craap-method#:~:text=When%20evaluating%20sources%20like%20Jotbot%2C,whether%20a%20source%20is%20trustworthy)[\[4\]](https://www.stevenson.edu/online/about-us/news/how-to-identify-reliable-information/#:~:text=1,that%20are%20up%20to%20date). If a source fails any of these, its trustworthiness is doubtful.
*   **Lateral Reading / SIFT Method:** Developed by Mike Caulfield, this four-step approach has become a gold standard for online research[\[11\]](https://mediahelpingmedia.org/basics/sift-for-fact-checking/#:~:text=SIFT%20teaches%20students%20how%20to,back%20to%20the%20original%20context)[\[12\]](https://hapgood.us/2019/06/19/sift-the-four-moves/#:~:text=First%2C%20when%20you%20first%20hit,Don%E2%80%99t). The steps are: **Stop** – before diving in, pause and _think_ about the source[\[13\]](https://mediahelpingmedia.org/basics/sift-for-fact-checking/#:~:text=,take%20a%20moment%20to%20reflect). Do you recognize the website or author? If not, don’t share or trust the information until you find out. **Investigate** – look up the publisher and author on other tabs (lateral reading). See what other sources say about them[\[14\]](https://mediahelpingmedia.org/basics/sift-for-fact-checking/#:~:text=,Find%20better%20coverage). For example, if you’re reading a health tip written by an unknown blog, a quick search might reveal a lack of credentials or prior misinformation. **Find better coverage** – search for other reporting on the same claim. Often it’s faster and more informative to read a reputable news outlet’s coverage or a fact-checker’s analysis of the topic[\[15\]](https://mediahelpingmedia.org/basics/sift-for-fact-checking/#:~:text=,media%20to%20understand%20its%20context)[\[6\]](https://newslit.org/tips-tools/tool-type/infographic/#:~:text=3,algorithms%20to%20bring%20you%20updates). This helps you understand the context, consensus, or controversy around the claim. **Trace (or “back to the source”)** – track any quoted data, images, or quotes back to the original document or study[\[16\]](https://mediahelpingmedia.org/basics/sift-for-fact-checking/#:~:text=for%20consensus%20and%20expert%20analysis,media%20to%20understand%20its%20context). For instance, an image or statistic might be accurate on its own, but if it’s taken out of context or miscaptioned in a viral post, tracing it back can reveal the full story.
*   **“Stop and Think”:** As Caulfield emphasizes, _stop before you trust or share anything_. If you don’t recognize the source, use at least a few minutes to investigate it before proceeding[\[12\]](https://hapgood.us/2019/06/19/sift-the-four-moves/#:~:text=First%2C%20when%20you%20first%20hit,Don%E2%80%99t). This simple habit prevents knee-jerk reactions.

Implementing these methods daily creates a reliable workflow. For example, when you see a breaking news story: do a **quick search** on the topic (News Literacy Project calls this _“often your best defense against misinformation”_)[\[6\]](https://newslit.org/tips-tools/tool-type/infographic/#:~:text=3,algorithms%20to%20bring%20you%20updates). See if established news or experts also report it. Simultaneously, **look for evidence** – does the story link to data or named studies? If a sensational claim stands alone without support, it’s a signal to doubt it[\[6\]](https://newslit.org/tips-tools/tool-type/infographic/#:~:text=3,algorithms%20to%20bring%20you%20updates). Always **seek credible sources** by default: prefer well-known news outlets, official reports, or academic publications over random social media posts[\[6\]](https://newslit.org/tips-tools/tool-type/infographic/#:~:text=3,algorithms%20to%20bring%20you%20updates). And practice patience – credible verification often takes time, so be wary of “breaking” posts that seem certain too fast[\[6\]](https://newslit.org/tips-tools/tool-type/infographic/#:~:text=3,algorithms%20to%20bring%20you%20updates).

## Fact-Checking Tools and Resources

In addition to manual checks, use dedicated fact-check resources. Websites like **Snopes**, **PolitiFact**, **FactCheck.org**, and similar organizations evaluate claims and publish detailed analyses. The UN advice page explicitly recommends tools such as _Google’s Fact Check Explorer_ or Snopes to debunk viral falsehoods[\[7\]](https://help.unhcr.org/slovakia/safe-online/information/#:~:text=One%20of%20the%20best%20ways,such%20as%20%2054%20Google%E2%80%99s). You can also use reverse-image searches (e.g. Google Images or TinEye) to see if a photo or graphic has been used in a different context. Browser extensions or services (e.g. NewsGuard, Hoaxy) can flag dubious domains or track viral rumors. In general, favor information that can be independently verified: official government, scientific or NGO websites are usually reliable because they follow editorial standards[\[17\]](https://help.unhcr.org/slovakia/safe-online/information/#:~:text=,procedures%2C%20and%20state%20provided%20assistance). For instance, humanitarian or public health organizations will clearly label urgent updates on crises. In contrast, be wary of sites with excessive ads, clickbait language, or no clear ownership – these are common traits of unreliable outlets[\[18\]](https://help.unhcr.org/slovakia/safe-online/information/#:~:text=%2A%20Up,also%20verifiable%20on%20other%20sites)[\[19\]](https://help.unhcr.org/slovakia/safe-online/information/#:~:text=,website%27s%20ownership%2C%20funding%2C%20and%20purpose).

Finally, remember that even technology is fallible: generative AI tools can produce realistic but incorrect content. Experts warn that AI outputs are _“not reliably factual”_ and often contain inaccuracies or biases[\[20\]](https://newslit.org/tips-tools/tool-type/infographic/#:~:text=1,complicated%20or%20specialized%20tasks%20more). Always treat AI-generated answers as starting points for research – verify them against authoritative sources.

## Workflow Recommendations

To make fact-checking automatic, integrate it into your reading habits:

*   **Use checklists:** Keep a mental or written checklist (e.g. CRAAP or SIFT) as you encounter news. Before sharing anything, mentally tick off criteria like author, date, evidence.
*   **Lateral reading:** Always open a new tab and do a quick search on unfamiliar content. A few minutes spent cross-referencing can catch many falsehoods[\[14\]](https://mediahelpingmedia.org/basics/sift-for-fact-checking/#:~:text=,Find%20better%20coverage)[\[6\]](https://newslit.org/tips-tools/tool-type/infographic/#:~:text=3,algorithms%20to%20bring%20you%20updates).
*   **Ask questions:** Be skeptical. As one guide puts it, if you don’t _know_ something, ask. Who benefits from this story? What did the data _actually_ say? If in doubt, reach out to experts – librarians, scholars or experienced journalists can often clarify or point to reliable information.
*   **Stay aware of biases:** Check _your_ biases. The IFLA infographic reminds us to _“check your biases”_ – we are more likely to accept information that confirms what we already believe[\[9\]](https://newslit.org/tips-tools/tool-type/infographic/#:~:text=Image%3A%20Bias%20lesson%20cover%20art,often%20fail%20to%20notice%20them). Try to consume a variety of perspectives and watch out for emotional triggers (hateful or extreme content is often manipulative).
*   **Use fact-check services:** If a claim seems important or suspicious, look it up on fact-checking sites. Many major news outlets now have fact-check sections (and even smartphone apps) summarizing debunked rumors.

Building these practices into your routine – even informally – will greatly improve your confidence. A helpful mindset is to think like an investigator or journalist: gather evidence before concluding. As Caulfield notes, vetting sources _“is about reconstructing the necessary context”_[\[21\]](https://hapgood.us/2019/06/19/sift-the-four-moves/#:~:text=When%20it%20comes%20to%20claims%2C,land%20on%20a%20better%20source). That way, you’re less likely to be misled by persuasive framing or decontextualized facts.

## Conclusion

No single trick will catch 100% of false content, but a combination of healthy skepticism and proven strategies makes a huge difference. Always cross-check important information against trusted sources, and err on the side of caution with sensational claims. As one media literacy guide warns, early “breaking” details often turn out to be incorrect[\[22\]](https://newslit.org/tips-tools/tool-type/infographic/#:~:text=Remember%3A%20Early%20details%20in%20news,the%20story%20continues%20to%20unfold). By **verifying before sharing** – using methods like SIFT and CRAAP and consulting fact-checkers – you can confidently filter out unreliable sources and rely only on factual, authentic information.
